From \(\) 94.00\(\) 92.00\(Equal - weight Underweight
LAM outperformed WFE during 2024- 25, driven by NAND, China & TSMC, but we don't expect growth to sustain into 2026.

LAM has regained market share led by NAND, China, and TSMC. After shipments underperformed WFE by 33ppt in 2023 due to a cyclical decline in NAND and China entity list impact, LAM outpaced WFE by 8ppt in 2024. We estimate another 22ppt outperformance in 2025 driven by NAND (2025 NAND WFE +102% y/y), China (50ppt+ outperformance vs Western peers), and share gains at TSMC.

But we aren't confident about NAND and China growth into 2026. We model LAM's 2026 system shipments to align closely with WFE (LAM +5% vs WFE +5%) as the company's growth drivers (China, NAND) slow after two very strong years (2024- 25). Despite our appreciation for LAM's NAND story (25pt share gain over the last decade), end- markets just aren't robust enough to drive further growth for LAM and NAND WFE. We expect growth to decelerate from 82% in 2025 to 3% in 2026. China Logic has been LAM's biggest growth driver since 2021 as the company expanded its share in the region. However, following 37%/35% y/y growth in 2024/2025, we don't foresee a reacceleration and model 3% growth in 2026. We project 8% growth in non- China logic driven by TSMC, but a slowdown in NAND & China (54% of shipments) limits total shipment growth. We don't think there is anything fundamentally wrong with LAM; it's just hard to see LAM outgrowing WFE in 2026, and expect relative share performance to lag as a result.

Estimates above street, but we think buy side is ahead of us. Our new CY26 revenue/EPS estimates of \(\) 21.5bn/\(\) 5.12\(are 3%/8\%\) above street, but we believe buy side estimates surpass MSE, capping share price upside even if street estimates were to align close to MSE. At their latest earnings, LAM guided SepQ revenue of\) \ \(5.2bn\) , 12% above street at \(\) 4.65bn\(but the stock fell 4.3% the next day, suggesting buy side estimates might have been even higher than the guide. Our PT of\) \ \(92\) , implying 10% downside, applies an 18x multiple to our CY26 EPS of \(\) 5.12\(vs\) 20x\(currently), 2 - turns ahead of the company's historical average (16x) to reflect share gains from 2024 - 25. We believe the stock is likely to be a relative under performer among large cap US SPE as the company faces a challenging 2026 setup.

Where could we be wrong: 1) China: we don't anticipate outperformance to the same magnitude as in 2025 (50ppt+), but the company could drive revenue growth above MSE. 2) TSMC: acceleration of 2nm builds could drive upside to MSE.
With this note, Shane Brett is assuming lead coverage of Lam Research (LRCX).

Debate: Can LAM outperform WFE for the 3rd year in a row?

Our View: After 2 strong years of outperformance, we model LAM's 2026 system shipments to track broadly in- line with WFE (LAM +5% vs WFE +5%) as the company's growth drivers (China, NAND) slow after 2 very strong years (2024- 25).

LAM has clawed back share since 2024. After underperforming WFE shipments by 33ppt in 2023 due to a cyclical decline in NAND and China entity list impact, LAM outperformed WFE by 8ppt in 2024 and we estimate another 22ppt outperformance in 2025. We estimate the company's share of WFE to have been 12.9% in 2022, which then declined to 8.9% in 2023, and following 2 years of outperformance the company's share now stands at 11.2%.

Debate: How durable is LAM's outperformance in China?

Our View: China Logic has been LAM's biggest growth driver since 2021 as the company has expanded their foundry logic market share in the region. However, following \(37\% /35\%\) y/y growth in 2024/2025 we don't expect a reacceleration from here and model \(3\%\) growth in 2026.

China Logic has been LAM's biggest growth driver. LAM's biggest growth driver from 2021 has been China Logic, as we estimate the company has expanded revenue in the region by \(2.2bn (+133\%)\) , compared to total revenue growth of \(21\%\) , non- China Logic at \(44\%\) and DRAM at \(20\%\) . The company's growth driver in China during 2019- 2022 was YMTC, as LAM was a key supplier during YMTC's ascent to more than 10x bit output during that timeframe and obtain \(6\%\) market share. LAM's market share declined by approx. 7ppt in 2023, partially due to YMTC being placed on the entity list. Since then, LAM has worked to diversify their customer base, and we believe the company has gained significant share with established customers such as Hua Hong and Huali but also with new customer projects.

Can the company gain further share? Tough, but not impossible. Historically, LAM's market share in China has been higher than their total WFE share due to the company's outsized share at Samsung's NAND fabs in China and YMTC. Following YMTC's addition to the entity list, LAM's China market share fell below total WFE market share in 2023, but we estimate that LAM's China market share surpassed total WFE market share in 2025. Western peers saw their China market share decline in 2025 as localization progressed, but LAM's market share increased as the company's growth tracked in- line with China local peers. We model LAM's China revenue to increase \(20\%\) y/y in 2025 (systems growth of \(32\%\) ) vs Western peers down \(20\%\) y/y. We don't think the company can continue to outgrow their Western peers to the same magnitude as 2025 but given the company's strong focus on both large and new customers in China, we wouldn't rule out LAM maintaining share and bucking localization worries that its Western peers face.

Should we be worried about Naura & AMEC? To an extent. We model China localization to increase from \(16\%\) in 2024 to \(30\%\) in 2026 led by Naura and AMEC. Our view had been

that localization has progressed further in memory than logic, as memory makers have needed to bring up local SPE makers due to being placed on the entity list. While Naura and AMEC are making progress in logic, companies like Hua Hong and Huali prefer LAM's tools to local alternatives, and we don't expect LAM's position with those customers to change. We don't have as much confidence on LAM's ability to continue gaining share at new customers as the company's product portfolio is relatively narrower than the likes of AMAT and TEL. LAM has clearly gained share in 2025, which makes us inclined to think that the company will continue to do well, but we are more favorable on LAM's position with larger Chinese customers than newer and smaller customers.

Debate: How durable is LAM's NAND strength?

Our View: As much as we like LAM's NAND story (25pt share gain over the last decade), end- markets just aren't strong enough to drive further growth for LAM and NAND WFE, and we model \(3\%\) shipment growth in 2026 (+82% in 2025).

LAM is the undeniable NAND leader. LAM's share of LAM/AMAT/TEL's NAND shipments has increased almost 25pts over the last decade, as the company has gone from \(29\%\) share in 2015 to \(51\%\) in 2025. LAM was the biggest market share gainer from the 3D NAND transition and continued to gain share through 2020- 2022 when NAND WFE entered a cyclical upcycle. We expect the company to maintain share during 2025- 2027 as LAM benefits from WFE investment being upgrade centric due to being the incumbent.

The 2026 outlook just isn't great. We estimate 2025 NAND WFE of \(10.2bn (+102\% y/y)\) and model LAM/AMAT/TEL/KLA's combined NAND shipments to increase \(96\%\) y/y in 2025. Spending was driven by capacity upgrades from 128/176- layer to 200- layer and above, and we estimate that of the 1,000kwpm of 128/176- layer NAND capacity in place as of 2024, approx. 660kwpm will be upgraded during 2025- 2026. We model 2026 NAND WFE of \(11.1bn (+9\% y/y)\) as we continue to expect customers to upgrade capacity, but we assume part of the 2025 strength came at the expense of 2026 as our brownfield assumptions are flat y/y. We model little to no brownfield ex- China, as we estimate upgrades can satisfy the \(53\%\) bit demand growth from 2024 to 2027.

NAND WFE intensity unlikely to surpass \(20\%\) . We aren't overly optimistic on the long- term growth prospects of NAND WFE and model WFE intensity to recover from \(8\%\) in 2024 to \(18\%\) in 2025 but flat line through 2027. We don't expect NAND WFE intensity to return to pre- 2022 levels \((30\% +)\) for 2 reasons: 1) Bit Demand: \(Y / y\) bit demand growth tracked above \(30\%\) during 2018- 2022 but has since moderated to mid- teens and we model \(9\%\) in 2025. Although eSSDs are seeing growth from datacenter demand, smartphones just aren't seeing the content growth that they saw during 2018- 2022. 2) DRAM: Hynix/Micron/Samsung have shifted their capex budgets towards DRAM, which has led to DRAM WFE intensity tracking higher vs pre- 2022 but overall memory WFE intensity tracking broadly flat. 3) It's not just layer count growth: Until 2022, NAND makers would pursue layer count growth (i.e. etch/dep investment) as the primary method of increasing bit density but NAND makers are now finding other ways to enable higher bit density. Examples include using lateral shrink by reducing wordline to reduce area overhead, using CBA (CMOS bonded array, wafer bonding) to individually optimize performance of the CMOS wafers and memory cell wafers to increase interface speed, and logical shrink (QLC) to increase density.

Debate: Is LAM a leading- edge logic share gainer and will they continue to gain share?

Our View: Leading- edge logic has been LAM's 2nd largest growth driver since 2021 on the back of revenue growth at TSMC. We believe the business will continue to grow, and be the largest source of revenue growth during 2025- 2027.

LAM's leading- edge logic business has done well. We estimate non- China logic to have been \(24\%\) of LAM's system shipments in 2021 but has grown to become \(29\%\) of shipments in 2025. By end- market, we estimate non- China logic to have been the 2nd largest growth driver from 2021. We believe that growth has been driven by share gain at TSMC.
LAM has done well at TSMC (relatively). Across our large cap US SPE coverage, our view on share position at TSMC is as follows:

- KLA 
- Share Gainer: KLA's share of TSMC capex averaged \(4.6\%\) in 2014-2019, \(5.6\%\) in 2020-2024, and we model \(6.6\%\) in 2025-2026. The company's growth has been driven by both process control intensity increasing and KLA's share gain.- AMAT 
- Share Loser: AMAT's share of TSMC capex has dropped from an average of \(19.1\%\) during FY15-19 to an average of \(14.1\%\) during FY21-24, with share peaking at \(21.0\%\) in FY18 but since falling to a low of \(13.5\%\) in FY24. AMAT has been a victim of TSMC's investment mix shifting away from etching and deposition, and towards EUV and process control.- LAM 
- (slight) Share Gainer: LAM's share of TSMC's capex has tracked at approx. \(6-8\%\) , with relative stability around \(7\%\) in recent years, which in the context of investment mix shifting away from etching and deposition, is share gains within LAM's SAM.
While KLA has been the undeniable share gainer at TSMC, we think LAM has done as well as they could given investment mix headwinds (less etch & dep) as well as fiercer competition (AMAT, TEL, ASM)

Leading- edge logic to drive growth through 2027. We estimate LAM's biggest growth drivers (\$) during 2023- 2025 to have been NAND and China logic, but we believe leading- edge logic and CSBG will be the company's biggest growth drivers during 2025- 2027 as growth in NAND and China logic slows. While TSMC's capex has returned to near- record levels seen in 1H23, the mix has shifted toward buildings, with equipment investment still muted. If equipment spending normalizes back to 80% of capex, we see y/y equipment spending growth on a flat \$40bn headline capex. We estimate LAM's TSMC revenue to increase 60% y/y in 2025, and model 11% growth in 2026.

No clear trigger for LAM's over/underperformance. Historical SPE share price performance and WFE trends have had the following relationships:

- KLA outperforms when Logic WFE > Memory WFE: KLA has outperformed AMAT/LAM when foundry logic WFE outperforms memory WFE.- AMAT outperforms when DRAM WFE > Total WFE: AMAT tends to outperform LAM when DRAM WFE outperforms total WFE.

Given LAM's outsized exposure to NAND, one would presume that LAM would outperform when NAND WFE outgrows WFE, but we don't find that to be true, likely due to 2 reasons: 1) There aren't many years when NAND WFE has outperformed total WFE, and 2) LAM's more recent growth has been driven by end-markets outside of NAND.

Relative performance vs AMAT impacted by valuation. Over the last decade, there hasn't been many occasions where LAM has consistently underperformed AMAT. A key reason for that is valuation as LAM has transitioned from trading at a discount vs AMAT to a premium over 3 phases during the last decade:

- 11% discount (2013-2018): AMAT was the SPE market share leader, and LAM's multiple was depressed due to the KLA-LAM merger (2015-2016)- 3% premium (2019-2022): LAM saw multiple expansion as the company gained share from the 3D NAND transition.- 13% premium (2023-): LAM's diversification strategy away from NAND and GM% expansion from their manufacturing shift to Malaysia has started to bear fruit.

Since Jan. 2025, the valuation premium has expanded to 20% as AMAT has seen multiple contraction due to execution issues and a lack of a growth driver, while LAM has seen multiple expansion on continued outperformance vs WFE.

We compared LAM's relative performance against AMAT during different phases of the memory cycle: in NAND up- cycles and DRAM up- cycles, and found that LAM's outperformance is not dependent on the memory cycle. Using NAND and DRAM ASP (WSTS), we removed seasonality and irregularities from our time series data to create a comparable and standardized view of memory pricing cycle regimes. This allowed us to identify periods of NAND and DRAM up- cycles, defined as the recovery and expansion of memory pricing from trough to peak.

We then compared LAM and AMAT's stock performance across these ASPs cycle regimes from 2005 to the present, as well as over the full time period. Our results suggest memory cycle is not a determining factor on LAM's over/under- performance against AMAT. Over the last decade, LAM has outperformed AMAT through cycle. While NAND up- cycles tend to coincide with stronger relative performance from LAM, DRAM up- cycles still more often than not see LAM outperforming. Periods when AMAT outperformed are better understood as being driven by company- specific factors, rather than by the underlying memory pricing cycle.
